Charlists

<!-- livebook:{"break_markdown":true} -->

charlists are a blind spot because Ruby uses both " and ' for strings, but in Elixir they are different!

```elixir
<<99, 97, ?t>>

```



```elixir
[99, 97, 116]

```

```elixir
'cat'
```

```elixir
"cat" == ~c"cat"
```

```elixir
[99, 97, 116]
```

## data type definition.

```elixir
defmodule Counter do
  # construct
  def new(input) do
    String.to_integer(input)
  end

  # reduce
  def add(acc, number) do
    acc + number
  end

  # convert
  def show(acc) do
    "The ants arrrr is #{acc}"
  end
end
```

```elixir
input = "42"
```

```elixir
import Counter

input 
|> new() 
|> add(1) 
|> add(1) 
|> add(-1) 
|> show()
```

```elixir
input = "0"
list_of_numbers = [1, 2, 3]
Enum.reduce(list_of_numbers, Counter.new(input), fn i, acc -> Counter.add(acc, i) end) |> Counter.show()
```

```elixir
[first, second, third] = list_of_numbers
input 
|> Counter.new()
|> Counter.add(first)
|> Counter.add(second)
|> Counter.add(third)
|> Counter.show()
```

